</div>
<p>The <b>common nightingale</b> or simply <b>nightingale</b> (<i>Luscinia megarhynchos</i>), also known as <b>rufous nightingale</b>, is a small <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passerine" title="Passerine">passerine</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> best known for its powerful and beautiful song. It was formerly classed as a member of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thrush_(bird)" title="Thrush (bird)">thrush</a> family <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turdidae" title="Turdidae" class="mw-redirect">Turdidae</a>, but is now more generally considered to be an <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_World_flycatcher" title="Old World flycatcher">Old World flycatcher</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscicapidae" title="Muscicapidae" class="mw-redirect">Muscicapidae</a>. It belongs to a group of more terrestrial species, often called <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chat_(bird)" title="Chat (bird)">chats</a>.</p>
<p></p>
